Articles.Content:
I have no idea what's going on, but, I have a model of a nozzle for an engine with multiple nozzles, and no matter WHAT I DO, I can't get the Blue Arrow in Unity on the model to point down instead of up. I heard in the past blue pointing down is important for an engine, while green is for RCS, but I can't get it to point down AT ALL. The nozzle is upright in Blender, like how the engines are in-game. The blue arrow is pointing up. I delete the model in Unity, flip the engine in Blender by 180, and then add it back into Unity, nothing. NOTHING. It stays how it was with the upright nozzle, DESPITE DELETING the ENTIRE UNITY PROJECT and starting fresh. Please, what can I do to fix this? It's driving me up the wall!

Also, I'm terribly sorry for sounding absolutely triggered right now, but I literally wasted my entire day making this thing EXPECTING things to go normal like before, but now I only have half an hour left of my day, so if I don't get this to work, I will be beyond ticked off. I get it's my fault for not taking a break, but this shouldn't even be happening at all. 

And also, yes, I know to rename the nozzle thrustTransform, but that is the least of my concerns right now.

Actually, I think I may have found a cheatsy way out of this, by rescaling on the Z axis to -1 instead of 1. Will this still work?

Now I have an even worse problem. My part isn't showing up at all... I just... What the heck happened in 1.2 that makes it impossible to make mods!?

there is no texture for the shader in unity,

also there is a lot of modules in the part.cfg, it's good to test it with as few as you can to reduce the field of research.

Look in the log file for errors

Sounds like a bad path somewhere

As Skalu pointed out, you have not assigned a texture for your shader. It's set to KSP/Specular, but you need to either select the texture or drag and drop it into the shader. If that doesn't help, make sure you named your .mu file "model", since you are calling on the model by "mesh = model.mu". Thats all I can think of off the top of my head. Your .cfg file looks good.

I've never had good results with mesh = model.mu.

Instead use  

MODEL
	{
	model = YourpartsDir/Parts/Command/model
	}

Where model is the name of your .mu and the Directory is your parts directory starting from the Gamedata folder.
